I love the rainbows that appear after a heavy summer shower. They are not the big, bright ones you see in picture books. No, my favourite rainbows are the shy, quiet ones.

They happen in the late afternoon. The sun dips low behind the hills, casting long, golden shadows across the garden. The air smells of wet earth and cut grass. Suddenly, a faint arc appears over the old oak tree. It is pale and soft, like a whisper of colour.

The red is barely there, just a hint of warmth. The blue is cool and calm, like the sky before dusk. It does not shout for attention. It simply sits there, gentle and fleeting.

I like these rainbows because they feel secret. It is as if the sky is sharing a little magic just with me. They remind me that beauty does not need to be loud to be special. When the light fades, the rainbow vanishes, leaving only the memory of its soft glow. It is a perfect, quiet moment in a busy world. I watch it until it disappears, feeling happy and calm. These gentle rainbows are my favourite because they teach me to look closely and appreciate the small, quiet wonders of life. [end of text]


